+      "sourceNotes": "Claim: Week 5 of the AI governance pilot is Iterate & Inherit and asks participants to give the build to a teammate, watch where it breaks, and produce a v2 | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 5 section, header: \"Week 4 was build. Week 5 is iterate. Take what you built, give it to a teammate, watch where it breaks, fix it.\")\nClaim: Week 5 Challenge instruction \"cut what's thin, sharpen what's vague, name the human checkpoint that has to stay\" | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 5 Challenge box: \"Take the teammate's feedback from Week 4. Cut what's thin, sharpen what's vague, name the human checkpoint that has to stay.\")\nClaim: The capstone door opens Week 5 with the Week 4 build as the seed | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 5 lead paragraph: \"The capstone door opens this week — your Week 4 build is the seed.\")\nClaim: AI Friday is the pilot's weekly group session where participants bring iteration work | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html — recurring AI Friday cadence starting Week 2)\nEditorial: The two-prompt Diff-Then-Decide loop (KEEP / FIX / CUT changelist, then constrained rewrite that touches only FIX items) is Preston's tactical move for Week 5 iteration. It mirrors the iterative-refinement pattern Anthropic recommends across prompt engineering documentation but the specific two-prompt structure and column labels are Preston's pedagogical framing.\nEditorial: Framing \"regeneration\" as the trap of one-shot iteration (a fresh prompt with no record of what changed) is Preston's diagnostic.\nEditorial: \"The capstone seed lives in the FIX column you signed off on. The v2 chat is downstream of that decision.\" is Preston's pedagogical close, tying the tactical loop back to the Week 5 capstone-scoping move.\nEditorial: Resource URL points to the pilot hub root; Week 5 block is currently display:none in pilot_hub.html as of 2026-05-05 morning. Pilot administrator will unhide the block on the cadence schedule. The Week 5 Challenge text cited above is in the source HTML and will surface when the block reveals.\nAdversarial review 20260505: Em-dash count: 0 (well under the 2-per-piece limit). Banned phrases scanned and absent: leverage, utilize, delve, navigate (metaphorical), landscape (metaphorical), ecosystem, synergy, robust, holistic, stakeholders, foster, enhance, align, transformative, empower, myriad, multifaceted, pivotal, spearhead, showcase, underscore, doing the heavy lifting, the real question is, what most people miss, this is where it gets interesting, it's not about, deep dive, unpack, move the needle, at the end of the day, however, moreover, furthermore, additionally, serves as, stands as, represents, functions as, operates as, groundbreaking, game-changing, revolutionary, passionate about, excited to share, the real story, here's the thing. Contrastive constructions (\"X, not Y\" / \"not X but Y\" / \"isn't X — it's Y\"): zero. Rhetorical questions in body: zero. Opens with concrete fact (Week 5 challenge asks for a v2). Closes with declarative landing (\"The v2 chat is downstream of that decision.\"). Word count main body: 261 (inside 240–280 band). Try This: 52 (inside 40–80 band). Each Editorial framing is tagged. Each external claim traces to pilot_hub.html or the AI Fluency framework, no invented statistics. Tip register: addresses participants directly via \"your\" and \"you\" without descending into TED-talk language.",
