       "content": "A 2023 field experiment from Harvard Business School, MIT, Wharton, and BCG ran 758 consultants through 18 realistic business tasks. Half had access to GPT-4. Inside what the researchers called the AI frontier (the tasks the model could handle), consultants with GPT-4 finished 12% more tasks, 25% faster, and produced work judged 40% higher in quality. Outside the frontier, where the model gave plausible but wrong answers, AI users did worse than the control group.\n\nThe finding worth carrying into Week 5: the productivity lift came from how people used the model. Pure access captured only a fraction of the available gain. The rest came from iteration. The researchers labeled two working patterns. Centaurs split work cleanly, handing whole pieces to the model. Cyborgs wove iteration through every step: draft, critique, redraft, hand to a colleague, fix what broke. Both patterns produced gains. Both required the user to know where the frontier sat and stop trusting the model past the edge.\n\nThat is the Week 5 inheritance test in research form. Week 4 asked you to build something worth keeping. Week 5 asks you to hand the build to a teammate and watch where it breaks. The Dell'Acqua paper says the same thing the pilot says. A build earns its keep through iteration. The first version is a guess about where the frontier sits. The second version, written after a teammate hits the edge, is the one that knows.\n\nThe trap is treating the first output as the final answer. The Cyborgs in the study did not.",
